#:blog{:title "The Blockchain Trilemma Is a Bounded Observation Problem"
       :date #inst "2026-03-01T08:00:00.000-00:00"
       :abstract
       [:p
        "The trilemma is usually framed as decentralization, security, and scalability. A more precise view is that it emerges from "
        [:strong "bounded observation"]
        ": nodes see different prefixes of global history, so they must pay to reconcile those views."]
       :content
       [:section.blog-article
        [:div.section-inner
         [:article
          :$blog-title
          :$blog-date

          [:p
           "A useful question is whether the blockchain trilemma is fundamental, or whether it is an artifact of how we model distributed systems."]

          [:p
           "The standard statement is well known: you cannot maximize "
           [:strong "decentralization"]
           ", "
           [:strong "security"]
           ", and "
           [:strong "scalability"]
           " at the same time. Most systems optimize two and pay with the third."]

          [:p
           "Terminology note: in this article, "
           [:code "prefix"]
           " means a log prefix (history prefix): the contiguous initial segment of an append-only stream from its start up to bound "
           [:code "t"]
           ". This is standard distributed-systems terminology in replication and consensus."]

          [:h2 "A More Structural Reformulation"]

          [:p
           "The trilemma can be reframed as an observation problem:"]

          [:pre
           [:code
            "Let S be global system history
Let Oi be node i's observed history

When Oi != Oj, nodes must reconcile
Reconciliation cost = communication + validation + storage + latency"]]

          [:p
           "In this framing, the trilemma is not mystical. It is the cost of reconciling partial observers into a coherent causal history."]

          [:h2 "Why the Universal Wave Function Analogy Helps"]

          [:p
           "If every observer had direct access to the same full state, consensus would be unnecessary:"]

          [:pre
           [:code
            "Idealized condition:
Oi = S for all i

Then:
No reconciliation
No fork resolution
No consensus rounds"]]

          [:p
           "That is why the universal wave function analogy is interesting. It isolates the core issue: consensus exists because observation is local, delayed, and incomplete."]

          [:h2 "Datom Stream Interpretation"]

          [:p
           "In Datom.world terms, global state is not a mutable object. It is an append-only history:"]

          [:pre
           [:code
            "S(t) = prefix(stream, t)"]]

          [:p
           "Each node observes a local prefix. Differences in observed prefix produce disagreement. Consensus is the protocol cost of reconciling those prefixes under adversarial conditions."]

          [:h2 "Why the Tradeoff Returns"]

          [:p
           "Even with a universal stream abstraction, physical constraints remain:"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "Propagation is finite"]
           [:li "Bandwidth is finite"]
           [:li "Verification is finite"]
           [:li "Storage and indexing are finite"]]

          [:p
           "So the trilemma does not vanish in real systems. It reappears as a consequence of bounded information propagation."]

          [:h2 "Conclusion"]

          [:p
           "A precise claim is: "
           [:strong "the blockchain trilemma is a consequence of bounded observation of a global history"]
           "."]

          [:p
           "This reframing aligns with Datom.world architecture: one immutable stream, many local interpreters, explicit causal reconciliation."]

